    intro_text: 'The checked suit is one of British tailoring\'s most enduring contributions to menswear — rooted in the cloth traditions of the Scottish Highlands and the English country estate, yet wholly at home in a modern city context. From the bold geometry of windowpane checks to the refined subtlety of glen plaid, a well-chosen checked suit communicates confidence and an understanding of fabric heritage. At William Ashford, our checked suits are cut for men who want character without clutter.',
    style_tips: `When wearing a checked suit, keep all other pattern elements minimal — a plain shirt and solid tie allow the cloth to speak for itself.\nGlen plaid and Prince of Wales checks work exceptionally well with pale blue or white shirts, which provide visual breathing room.\nA knitted tie in a tone drawn from within the check is a sophisticated alternative to a silk tie and suits the texture of woollen checked cloth.\nFor bolder checks, such as large windowpane or district checks, choose shoes and accessories in a single, neutral tone to avoid visual competition.\nHoundstooth suits in black and white pair beautifully with grey or charcoal accessories for a monochromatic but textured result.\nAvoid wearing a checked shirt or a patterned pocket square with a strongly checked suit — layering too many patterns creates noise rather than harmony.`,
