    intro_text: 'The velvet blazer occupies a singular position in British menswear — it is simultaneously the most luxurious and the most liberating garment a well-dressed man can own. Originally the preserve of the aristocracy at country house dinners, it has evolved into a versatile evening statement that works across a range of occasions, from formal dinners to stylish social gatherings. At William Ashford, our velvet blazers are cut in the finest cotton velvet, designed to be worn and admired.',
    style_tips: `A midnight navy or bottle green velvet blazer is more versatile than black — it creates contrast when worn with dark trousers and is visually richer under evening light.\nPair with slim black trousers and a black turtleneck for a Continental evening look that sidesteps the formality of black tie.\nFor a more traditional approach, wear over a white dress shirt with black trousers and a black silk bow tie — this reads as a relaxed take on black tie.\nVelvet attracts lint readily; use a soft brush or lint roller before wearing, always brushing in the direction of the pile.\nKeep accessories minimal with a velvet blazer — the fabric is statement enough; a simple gold lapel pin or pocket square suffices.\nAvoid wearing a velvet blazer with casual denim or sportswear; it demands trousers of equivalent quality — wool, silk, or fine cotton.`,
