    intro_text: 'The double-breasted suit is the most architecturally bold garment in tailoring — a jacket that commands attention, projects authority, and rewards the man who wears it with confidence. Once the preserve of City grandees and naval officers, the double-breasted suit has undergone a sustained revival and now represents the most sophisticated option in contemporary British tailoring. At William Ashford, our double-breasted suits are cut with a lean, modern silhouette that preserves the garment\'s authority without its historical bulk.',
    style_tips: `A double-breasted suit should always be worn buttoned when standing — the open double-breasted jacket is an unfinished, shapeless look that undermines the entire garment.\nChoose peak lapels for a double-breasted jacket — notch lapels are occasionally seen but lack the authority that the style demands.\nSlim trousers with a slight taper balance the broader, layered front of the jacket and create a modern, elongated silhouette.\nKeep shirts plain and ties simple — the jacket itself is the statement; over-accessorising competes with its natural authority.\nNavy and charcoal are the most versatile ground colours for double-breasted suits; they work across business, formal, and smart-casual contexts with ease.\nFor a contemporary update, try a double-breasted suit in a mid-grey with a fine texture — worn with a white shirt and no tie for a modern, European approach to tailoring.`,
